post_text:
Greetings Wyandotte Public Schools parents and patrons,
According to the State‚Äôs Color system, we are in Orange Protocol again for next week. That means we will continue with the A/B scheduling for the following week according to our adaptation to the Orange Protocol system. ‚ÄúA group‚Äù students will continue on-site instruction on Monday and Wednesday this coming week and ‚ÄúB group‚Äù students will continue on-site instruction on Tuesday and Thursday. We will re-assess again next Friday for the following week. I think it is good to consider the direction Ottawa County is trending in terms of new COVID-19 cases. The percent of cases that we rely on, starting from the first week of school has steadily increased every week and has doubled over the last week from the previous number. We say this to remind you to please be as vigilant as possible, report exposures and positive cases, and help us keep up to date information to avoid a prolonged move to full time distance learning.
Thank you and have a great weekend.
Steve Buckingham, WHS Principal

SCHOOL LUNCH INFORMATION:
Beginning immediately ALL STUDENTS and children, 0-18 years of age, may receive free meals through the Wyandotte child nutrition program. Oklahoma has been granted a waiver through December 31st for this program or until federal funding runs out. It‚Äôs still very important that you complete the free/reduced meal application. We are working to provide lunches for students on "virtual days" with a drive-thru pickup. More information will be available next week. Keep an eye out!

post_text: We have been handing out today and will hand out again tomorrow, individually wrapped water bottles. There are care instructions that come with the water bottles that indicate that they need to be washed before use, hand wash only, and avoid high temperatures. These water bottles are to be used specifically for our newly installed touchless water systems. Parents, please hand wash these, help your child mark them appropriately so that they can tell theirs from others, and then send them back to school so that they have them available to use.

post_text: Just a reminder as we posted last week, "We will start school with our Hybrid Learning (A/B schedule). ‚ÄúA‚Äù students' first day is August 13 and ‚ÄúB‚Äù students' first day will be August 14. We plan to continue our Hybrid Learning (A/B schedule) during the week of August 17th through August 21st so we can practice this schedule and correct any unanticipated problems. Students and staff will be required to wear face coverings while on the bus and while passing in the hallways. When students are in the classroom where socially distancing is possible, masks will be optional." #BFND

post_text:
Good afternoon Wyandotte Family,
We wanted to remind everyone that the enrollment procedures for the 20/21 school year are via Google Form that can be found on our website and Facebook pages. Please fill out the Google Form for enrollment so that we can make sure your child gets the classes he/she wants to be in. If you have already done so, you do not have to do it again. We currently have about 75% of our students who have responded. We need to get really close to that 100% number so that we can know what our logistics look like for the upcoming school year before we get too close to school.

Thank you and have a great day!

Good afternoon parents and patrons,

This article has a reasonably accurate description of what the current re-entry plan looks like without further changes in federal, state, and local conditions changing. We know all of you have been curious to see what this will look like, but we wanted to make sure we were being responsible with the information we put out. Please know these things are subject to change at any given point due to an ever-changing political, social, and health climate. Thank you for your patience to this point. We will be following guidelines highly similar to this when we start back August 13.

post_text:
One of the questions being asked the most is this: what about the chromebook that my child has? When do we check them in? The answer is: you won't.

Students will be keeping them for the summer and bring them back with them to school in the Fall. Please store them in a safe, clean, dry place with all attachments in the case.

In the event that your child is a senior or is not attending Wyandotte Public Schools next year, you can turn them in Thursday, May 7th or Monday, May 11th.

Bear in mind, this is the same chromebook they will be using through their entire school career at Wyandotte Public Schools, so take good care of it!

Thank you and have a great summer!

post_text:
In any given year, we are blessed to have some of the best teachers you can find at Wyandotte High School. This year, they were put to the test in extraordinary ways. From a summer flood that did damage to the school and left us without internet and phones all the way into the first couple weeks of school, a wind storm that damaged homes and the school to some degree, two different flu-vacations, and ending with a full quarter worth of distance learning due to a pandemic . . . .they've been pushed to the limit! They did it without batting an eye. They're an incredible group of people. Help us say thank you this week to the teachers of Wyandotte High School!

#BFND

They did it without batting an eye. They're an incredible group of people. Help us say thank you this week to the teachers of Wyandotte High School!

Parents, guardians, and patrons of Wyandotte Elementary School:

We will begin supply pick up starting next week (check the dates listed below). Pick up will be between the hours of 11 am-12:30 pm to coincide with lunch pick up. Someone will be in front of the Superintendent's office to direct you. We hope this runs smoothly and ask that you follow the guidelines of coming on your assigned day. Please be patient as we will try to be as efficient as possible.

We hope everyone is working hard on their school work and keeping safe. If there are any questions please feel free to contact me at vlewis@wyandotte.k12.ok.us.

Thursday, April 30th A-H
Monday, May 4th I-R
Thursday, May 7th S-Z

post_text:
Beginning Tuesday, March 24th we will provide a meal pick up program for children and community individuals 18 years of age and younger. There is no cost for these meals. The drive through pick up will be in front of the HS from 11:00 a.m.-12:30 p.m. daily. Individuals will receive a lunch for that day and a breakfast for the following day.

Currently, according to Federal Child Nutrition guidelines, all individuals must be present to receive meals. We will analyze the success of this program and adjust accordingly. Hope you are having a great Spring Break. - Troy Gray Superintendent #BFND

post_text: Today the State Board of Education voted in favor of mandatory closure of all Oklahoma public schools from March 17 through April 6. I know there are a lot of unanswered questions. This week we will have a Zoom meeting with the State Superintendent and I will meet with area superintendents to game plan. We appreciate your support and understanding. I will continue to relay information as it becomes available and inform you about local decisions impacting your students. Enjoy your Spring Break and GO BEARS! -Superintendent Troy Gray #BFND

post_text: Wyandotte Public Schools would like to welcome Mrs. Tammy Miller as she joins our Wyandotte family. She comes to Wyandotte after having taught for 22 years in Missouri. She has a Master‚Äôs degree in Education. She has taught third and fourth grades in the Seneca and Neosho school districts. She lives in Neosho and love to spend time with her four children and all of her grandchildren. She is very much looking forward to this new school year and getting the opportunity to meet all of her new fourth graders. Welcome to Wyandotte Mrs. Miller!

post_text:
OKLAHOMA'S PROMISE:
IMPORTANT REMINDER:
All 8th-10th grade parent/guardians.....

Oklahoma's Promise offers qualified Oklahoma students an opportunity to earn a scholarship for college tuition. To apply, 1) must be an Oklahoma resident, 2) must enroll in the 8th, 9th or 10th grade, and 3) the parents'/legal guardian federal adjusted gross income must not exceed $55,000 per year.

Application: The link to the Oklahoma's Promise home page is below. You can also receive a paper copy from your school counselor or print one from the site.

Applications are due by July 1, 2020.

**Please note that even if you make more than the allotted amount of $55,000, APPLY! Because even if you don't get accepted and your income situation changes from the time you apply to when your student graduates, you are in the system and can call and STILL QUALIFY!**

If you have any questions, feel free to contact our school counselor!

https://www.okhighered.org/okpromise/
